The second firm to emerge was Solarex, also founded in 1973 by Hungarian immigrants Joseph Lindmayer and Peter Varadi. They did not have any luck courting venture capitalists either, visiting 20 of them without success, and developing “allergic reactions if somebody mentioned the word ‘venture capitalist’” in the process [(
 
  64
 ), pp. 19, 192]. Bill Yerkes, who founded the third major PV firm Solar Technology International (STI) in 1975, visited an estimated 75 venture capital firms [(
 
  73
 ), p. 44] before selling his firm to the oil company Arco 2 years later.
